<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n53122ab"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53122ab">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53122ab"> 122(ab)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lotus, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53122ab"><li>FW 60.11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n53122ab">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n53122ab">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53122ab">MS BL 47476b-178</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:377 <a name="cd10" href="../../ff/fdra/cda.htm#cd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/cd10.htm#n53122ab">Draft: I.3&sect;1.10</a>/2.10/3.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Un jour, on dit, devant le prince, que l&apos;herbe, aux for&ecirc;ts, devenait tendre, que les oiseaux du printemps chantaient dans les arbres et que, sur les &eacute;tangs, s&apos;ouvr&acirc;ient les grands <mark>lotus</mark>. La nature &eacute;tait d&eacute;livr&eacute;e des liens o&ugrave; l&apos;avait tenue la saison froide. Les jardins, autour de la ville, &eacute;taient par&eacute;s de fleurs gracieuses, les jardins aim&eacute;s des jeunes femmes. Alors, tel un &eacute;l&eacute;phant qui fut longtemps encha&icirc;n&eacute; dans une &eacute;table, le prince eut l&apos;ardent d&eacute;sir de sortir du palais. <small> A. Ferdinand Herold, <a name="AFHB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#AFHB"><cite title="source">La Vie Du Bouddha</cite></a> (1922) 40</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: One day in Spring as in the pools in the palace the lotus was unfolding its petals and the flowers everywhere were in bloom, Siddharta felt an ache to leave the palace. Unhappy at this, the king ordered that no sight of suffering of any kind be allowed to distract the visits of the prince to the countryside around and this was done. The god or Deva determined nonetheless to frustrate the king&apos;s design and to awaken in the young man a thirst for truth. On one trip so, Siddharta met the Deva in the guise of an old man and thus learned of old age. On another time he met the Deva as a sick man and thus learned of sickness, of suffering and disease. On a third occasion, the Deva appeared before him in the semblance of a corpse and thus the prince learned of death itself.] [In text with Lettuceland: Ireland.] </mm> </dd></dl>
